ce:section.ce:para:
The b-SiCDs were synthesized by a one-step hydrothermal procedure according to the reported method (Fig. S1) [40,41], and QDs with red and green colors were prepared in the aqueous phase by refluxing for different times [42]. The detailed preparation procedures are described in the Supporting Information. The related characterization results are shown in Fig. S2 and Fig. S3. Then, b-SiCDs were embedded into SiO2 NPs in situ by a modified Stöber method utilizing tetraethyl orthosilicate as a silica precursor and ammonium hydroxide (NH3·H2O) as a catalyst to obtain b@SiO2. During the synthesis of b@SiO2, the “Si−O−C” structure existed in b-SiCDs was also hydrolyzed by NH3·H2O and covalently bound with the silicon element in SiO2 NPs (Fig. S4) [43]. Compared to b-nonSiCDs@SiO2 (the detailed preparation procedures are shown in Supporting Information), the b@SiO2 have stronger robustness and fluorescence brightness, which can prevent b-SiCDs from leaking into solution and is conducive to colorimetric analysis (Fig. 1
                        ). Subsequently, r-QDs and g-QDs were electrostatically self-assembled on the surface of b@SiO2 using PDDA as a bridge to construct b@SiO2@r and b@SiO2@g, respectively. Notably, the functionalization of b@SiO2 via PDDA not only provides a homogeneous and positive charged surface for the loading of QDs, but also retains the inherent structure and properties (e.g., dispersibility and intrinsic optical performance) of the b@SiO2 
                        [44,45]. Meanwhile, the modification principle using PDDA is less restricted and more timesaving in comparison with other modification principle such as covalent linkage between carboxyl and amine through usage of EDC/NHS.
